//Linked Structures (each known as node) -> Dynamic -> Linear or Non-linear

//Advantage:
//More flexible, No storage space wasted with initial storage for cells in an array, No need to check in adding operations if already full

//Disadvanatge:
//Linked structure's nodes will have two referneces, array's cell will only have one; with the same size, arrays will take less space.

//Adding node to the front:
//To insert a node in the middle of a linked list, first locate the current node. Set the new node to point to the node that current references, then update current to point to the new node, inserting it into the list.

//Adding a node to the middle/back
//To add to the back, simply don’t update new element’s next link, just update the old rear’s next to the new element.

//Deleting a node from the front
//To remove the first node, update `front` to reference the second node. The original first node becomes unreferenced and is later garbage-collected by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).

//Deleting a node from the middle (or rear):
//To remove the last element, simply set the penultimate element’s next to null

//LinearNode
public class LinearNode<T>{
  private T element; 
  private LinearNode<T> next; //Node after this one

  public LinearNode(){
    next = null;
    element = null;
  }
  public LinearNode(T elem) {
    next = null;
    element = elem;
  }
  public LinearNode<T> getNext() {return next;}
  public void setNext(LinearNode<T> node) { next = node;}
  public T getElement(){ return element;}
  public void setElement(T elem) {element = elem;}
}

